--Simple Yes/No shutdown thingy, asks if you want to shutdown if yes, shutdown. If no, Exits.
simple enough tbh
on the 10th line in at the end you can see "20", thats the timeout, you can change it to 0 if you want
the shutdown the happen instantly.

Option Explicit

Dim result
result = MsgBox ("Shutdown?", vbYesNo, "Yes/No Exm")
Select Case result
    Case vbYes
        MsgBox("shuting down ...")
        Dim objShell
        Set objShell = WScript.CreateObject("WScript.Shell")
        objShell.Run "C:\WINDOWS\system32\shutdown.exe -r -t 20"
    Case vbNo
        MsgBox("Ok")
End Select

And you could be a real dick and change it up a bit...

Option Explicit

Dim result
result = MsgBox ("Are you sure you want to delete System32?", vbYesNo, "Windows Firewall")
Select Case result
    Case vbYes
        MsgBox("Windows can no longer function properly, try re-installing Windows and reboot.")
        Dim objShell
        Set objShell = WScript.CreateObject("WScript.Shell")
        objShell.Run "C:\WINDOWS\system32\shutdown.exe -r -t 0"
    Case vbNo
        MsgBox("Windows can not function without C:\WINDOWS\System32. Try re-installing Windows or replacing the hard drive. For further information contact Microsoft https://www.support.microsoft.com/id?=EN-US")
        Dim objShell
        Set objShell = WScript.CreateObject("WScript.Shell")
        objShell.Run "C:\WINDOWS\system32\shutdown.exe -r -t 0"
End Select

--So when you click the file it will popup with a message box asking if you want to shut down, if you press "No" it exits the message box and youre
all good!
But
If you press "Yes" then it will shutdown the computer, simple as that tbh.
